[[File:Fidel Pag<U+00E9>s visiting an injured person in Melilla in the 1909 campaign.gif|thumb|250px|[[Fidel Pag<U+00E9>s]] visiting an injured man at the Docker Hospital in [[Melilla]], Spain during the [[Second Melillan campaign]] in 1909. The Docker Hospital was renamed after Pag<U+00E9>s in 1926.]]

The '''history of neuraxial anesthesia''' goes back to 1885.

==19th century==
Although some credit [[James Leonard Corning]] (1855{{ndash}}1923), a [[neurology|neurologist]] from New York,<ref name=Corning1885>Corning JL: Spinal anaesthesia and local medication of the cord. N Y Med J 1885; 42:483-5</ref><ref name=Corning1888>Corning JL: A further contribution on local medication of the spinal cord, with cases. N Y Med Rec 1888: 291-3</ref> German surgeon [[August Bier]] (1861{{ndash}}1949) is more widely recognized as the first to perform [[spinal anaesthesia|spinal anesthesia]] for surgery, on August 16, 1898.<ref name=Bier1899>{{cite journal|last=Bier|first=A|authorlink=August Bier|title=Versuche uber cocainisirung des ruckenmarkes (Experiments on the cocainization of the spinal cord)|language=German|journal=Deutsche Zeitschrift fur Chirurgie|volume=51|issue=|pages=361<U+2013>9|year=1899|pmid=|pmc=|doi=|url=}}</ref><ref name=Wulf1998>{{cite journal|last=Wulf|first=HFW|title=The centennial of spinal anesthesia|journal=Anesthesiology|volume=89|issue=2|pages=500<U+2013>6|year=1998|doi=10.1097/00000542-199808000-00028|pmid=9710410|pmc=|url=http://journals.lww.com/anesthesiology/pages/articleviewer.aspx?year=1998&issue=08000&article=00028&type=fulltext}}</ref>

==20th century==
The administration of anesthesic agents via the epidural route was first reported in 1901, mostly for the treatment of [[urology|urological]] diseases.{{cn|date=June 2012}} Several techniques were later developed, but were slow to gain popularity.<ref name=Diz2002/>

In 1921, Spanish military surgeon [[Fidel Pag<U+00E9>s]] (1886{{ndash}}1923) developed the modern technique of lumbar epidural anesthesia,<ref name=Pages1921>{{cite journal|last=Pag<U+00E9>s|first=F|authorlink=Fidel Pag<U+00E9>s|title=Anestesia metam<U+00E9>rica|language=Spanish|journal=Revista de Sanidad Militar|volume=11|issue=|pages=351-4|year=1921|pmid=|pmc=|doi=|url=}}</ref> which was popularized in the 1930s by Italian surgery professor [[Achille Mario Dogliotti]] (1897{{ndash}}1966).<ref name=Diz2002>J. C. Diz, A. Franco, D. R. Bacon, J. Rupreht, and J. Alvarez (eds.); ''The history of anesthesia: proceedings of the Fifth International Symposium'', Elsevier (2002), pp. 205-6, 0-444-51003-6</ref> Dogliotti is known for describing a "loss-of-resistance" technique, involving constant application of pressure to the plunger of a syringe to identify the epidural space whilst advancing the Tuohy needle <U+2014> a technique sometimes referred to as [[Dogliotti's principle]].<ref name=Dogliotti1933>{{cite journal|last=Dogliotti|first=AM|title=Research and clinical observations on spinal anesthesia: with special reference to the peridural technique|journal=Anesthesia & Analgesia|volume=12|issue=2|pages=59<U+2013>65|year=1933|pmid=|pmc=|doi=|url=http://www.anesthesia-analgesia.org/content/12/2/59.full.pdf}}</ref> [[Eugen Aburel|Eug<U+00E8>ne Aburel Bogdan]] (1899{{ndash}}1975) was a Romanian surgeon and obstetrician who in 1931 was the first to describe blocking the [[lumbar plexus]] during early labor, followed by a caudal epidural injection for the [[Childbirth#Second_stage:_fetal_expulsion|expulsion phase]].<ref name=Aburel1931>{{cite journal|last=Aburel|first=E|authorlink=Eugen Aburel|title=L'Anesth<U+00E9>sie locale continue prolong<U+00E9>e en obst<U+00E9>trique|language=French|journal=Bull Soc Obst et Gyn de Paris|volume=|issue=|pages=|year=1931|pmid=|pmc=|doi=|url=}}</ref><ref name=Aldretee2004>{{cite journal|last=Aldrete|first=JA|last2=Cabrera|first2=H|last3=Wright|first3=AJ|title=Manuel Martinez Curbelo And Continuous Lumbar Epidural Anesthesia|journal=Bulletin of Anesthesia History|volume=22|issue=4|pages=1<U+2013>8|year=2004|pmid=20503747|pmc=|doi=|url=http://aha.anesthesia.wisc.edu/Bulletin/October_2004.pdf}}</ref>

Beginning in October 1941, [[Robert Andrew Hingson]] (1913{{ndash}}1996), Waldo B. Edwards and James L. Southworth, working at the [[Marine Hospital Service|United States Marine Hospital]] at Stapleton, on Staten Island in New York, developed the technique of continuous caudal anesthesia.<ref name=Edwards1942>{{cite journal|last=Edwards|first=WB|last2=Hingson|first2=RA|title=Continuous caudal anesthesia in obstetrics|journal=American Journal of Surgery|volume=57|issue=3|pages=459<U+2013>64|year=1942|pmid=|pmc=|doi=10.1016/S0002-9610(42)90599-3|url=}}</ref><ref name=Hingson1942>{{cite journal|last=Hingson|first=RA|last2=Edwards|first2=WB|title=Continuous Caudal Anesthesia During Labor and Delivery|journal=Anesthesia and Analgesia|volume=21|issue=|pages=301<U+2013>11|year=1942|pmid=|pmc=|doi=|url=}}</ref><ref name=Hingson1943>{{cite journal|last=Hingson|first=RA|last2=Edwards|first2=WB|title=Comprehensive review of continuous caudal analgesia for anesthetists|journal=Anesthesiology|volume=4|issue=2|pages=181<U+2013>96|year=1943|pmid=|pmc=|doi=10.1097/00000542-194303000-00010|url=http://journals.lww.com/anesthesiology/Citation/1943/03000/Comprehensive_Review_of_Continuous_Caudal.10.aspx}}</ref><ref name=Rosenberg1999>{{cite journal|last=Rosenberg|first=H|title=Robert Andrew Hingson, M.D.: OB analgesia pioneer (1913-1996)|journal=American Society of Anesthesiologists Newsletter|volume=63|issue=9|pages=12<U+2013>13|year=1999|pmid=|pmc=|doi=|url=http://www.woodlibrarymuseum.org/Finding_Aid/hingson/hingson.pdf}}</ref> Hingson and Southworth first used this technique in an operation to remove the [[varicose veins]] of a Scottish merchant seaman. Rather than removing the caudal needle after the injection as was customary, the two surgeons experimented with a continuous caudal infusion of local anesthetic. Hingson then collaborated with Edwards, the chief [[obstetrics|obstetrician]] at the Marine Hospital, to study the use of continuous caudal anesthesia for analgesia during childbirth. Hingson and Edwards studied the caudal region to determine where a needle could be placed to deliver anesthetic agents safely to the spinal nerves without injecting them into the cerebrospinal fluid.<ref name=Hingson1943/>

The first use of continuous caudal anesthesia in a laboring woman was on January 6, 1942, when the wife of a [[United States Coast Guard]] sailor was brought into the Marine Hospital for an emergency Caesarean section. Because the woman suffered from rheumatic heart disease ([[heart failure]] following an episode of [[rheumatic fever]] during childhood), her doctors believed that she would not survive the stress of labor but they also felt that she would not tolerate general anesthesia due to her heart failure. With the use of continuous caudal anesthesia, the woman and her baby survived.<ref name=HingsonJAMA1943>{{cite journal|last=Hingson|first=RA|last2=Edwards|first2=WB|title=Continuous Caudal Analgesia in Obstetrics|journal=Journal of the American Medical Association|volume=121|issue=4|pages=225<U+2013>9|year=1943|pmid=|pmc=|doi=10.1001/jama.1943.02840040001001|url=}}</ref>

The first described placement of a lumbar epidural catheter was performed by [[P<U+00ED>o Manuel Mar<U+00ED>a Mart<U+00ED>nez Curbelo]] (5 June 1906{{ndash}}1 May 1962) on January 13, 1947.<ref>[http://articulos.sld.cu/editorhome/archives/8890 Dr. P<U+00ED>o Manuel Mart<U+00ED>nez Curbelo (in Spanish)]</ref><ref>[http://www.sld.cu/galerias/pdf/sitios/anestesiologia/la_anestesia_epidural_continua.pdf LA ANESTESIA EPIDURAL CONTINUA POR VIA LUMBAR: ANTECEDENTES Y DESCUBRIMIENTO (in Spanish)]</ref> Curbelo, a Cuban anesthesiologist, introduced a 16 gauge Tuohy needle into the left flank of a 40 year-old woman with a large [[ovarian cyst]]. Through this needle, he introduced a 3.5 [[French catheter scale|French]] [[ureter]]al catheter made of elastic [[silk]] into the lumbar epidural space. He then removed the needle, leaving the catheter in place and repeatedly injected 0.5% percaine ([[cinchocaine]], also known as dibucaine) to achieve anesthesia. Curbelo presented his work on September 9, 1947, at the 22nd Joint Congress of the [[International Anesthesia Research Society]] and the International College of Anesthetists, in New York City.<ref name=Aldretee2004/><ref name=Curbelo1949>{{cite journal|last=Martinez Curbelo|first=M|title=Continuous peridural segmental anesthesia by means of a ureteral catheter|journal=Curr Res Anesth Analg|volume=28|issue=1|pages=13<U+2013>23|year=1949|pmid=18105827|pmc=|doi=|url=}}</ref>

